if 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{a}$
\end_inset

 is constant between years 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a+t-1$
\end_inset

.
 Now the total adult abundance relative to new incoming adults is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
N_{y,A}=\sum_{a\geqslant\alpha}N\left(y,\alpha\right)\left(\frac{\phi_{A}}{\rho}\right)^{a-\alpha}=\frac{N\left(y,\alpha\right)}{1-\frac{\phi_{A}}{\rho}},
\]

\end_inset

which we can rearrange to get 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
N\left(y,\alpha\right)=\left(1-\frac{\phi_{A}}{\rho}\right)N_{y,A}.
\]

\end_inset

We can consider the same cohort,
 one year earlier as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
N\left(y-1,\alpha-1\right)\ensuremath{\phi_{J}=}\left(1-\frac{\phi_{A}}{\rho}\right)N_{y,A},
\]

\end_inset

i.e.,
 the abundance of oldest surviving juveniles (age 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha-1$
\end_inset

) in year 
\begin_inset Formula $y-1$
\end_inset

 (LHS) equals the adults of age 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 in year 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 (RHS).
 Rearranging and advancing the year by 1,
 gives:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
N\left(y,\alpha-1\right) & =\phi_{J}^{-1}\left(1-\frac{\phi_{A}}{\rho}\right)N_{y+1,A}\nonumber \\
 & =\left(\rho\phi_{J}\right)^{-1}\left(1-\frac{\phi_{A}}{\rho}\right)N_{y,A}\label{eq:Nyalpha--1}
\end{align}

\end_inset

which gives us the abundance of age 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha-1$
\end_inset

 individuals in year 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

